04735nam a22006015i 9780822391654DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223916547 a10.1515/97808223916542doi  a(DE-B1597)554290  a(OCoLC)662618995  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aLIT0080302bisacsh1 aMack, Edward, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aManufacturing Modern Japanese Literature :bPublishing, Prizes, and the Ascription of Literary Value /cEdward Mack; ed. by Rosalind C. Morris, Michael Dutton, Harry Harootunian, Rey Chow. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (331 p.) :b6 photos, 11 tables, 3 maps, 8 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia-Pacific: Culture, Politics, and Society : 4400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Publishing and the Creation of an Alternate Economy of Value -- t1. Modernity as Rupture: The Concentration of Print Capital -- t2. The Stability of the Center: Tokyo Publishing and the Great Kanto Earthquake -- t3. The Static Canon: Kaizosha’s Complete Works of Contemporary Japanese Literature -- t4. Defining and Defending Literary Value: Debates, 1919–1935 -- t5. The Dynamic Canon: The Akutagawa and Naoki Prizes for Literature -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEmphasizing how modes of book production, promotion, and consumption shape ideas of literary value, Edward Mack examines the role of Japan’s publishing industry in defining modern Japanese literature. In the late nineteenth century and early twentieth, as cultural and economic power consolidated in Tokyo, the city’s literary and publishing elites came to dominate the dissemination and preservation of Japanese literature. As Mack explains, they conferred cultural value on particular works by creating prizes and multivolume anthologies that signaled literary merit. One such anthology, the Complete Works of Contemporary Japanese Literature (published between 1926 and 1931), provided many readers with their first experience of selected texts designated as modern Japanese literature. The low price of one yen per volume allowed the series to reach hundreds of thousands of readers. An early prize for modern Japanese literature, the annual Akutagawa Prize, first awarded in 1935, became the country’s highest-profile literary award. Mack chronicles the history of book production and consumption in Japan, showing how advances in technology, the expansion of a market for literary commodities, and the development of an extensive reading community enabled phenomena such as the Complete Works of Contemporary Japanese Literature and the Akutagawa Prize to manufacture the very concept of modern Japanese literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCanon (Literature). 0aJapanese literaturexPublishing. 0aLiterary prizeszJapan. 0aLiterature publishingzJapan. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacsh1 aChow, Rey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDutton, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarootunian, Harry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMorris, Rosalind C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822391654zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822391654423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822391654/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  